0","1180":"1180","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Le Brook, Ilchester, Somerset, England":"Ilchester, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brooke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Brook  , which preserves a trace of the Old English dative singular case, originally used after a preposition (e.g. ‘at the brook’).","History: In 1650, Robert and Mary Mainwaring Brooke brought ten children and a number of servants with them from England to MD, where Robert became governor. Although the fourteen known contemporary Brooke immigrants in VA included Robert's brothers Richard and Humphrey, the relationships of the others are unknown. Brooke family memorials remain in the Anglican church at Whitchurch, Hampshire, England."],"variants":[{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Brooke was born in 1180, in Ilchester, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Arundel De Brooke, was 20 and his mother, Edeline de Cobham, was 18. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1231, in his hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1180–1231":"1180–1231","1220–1259":"1220–1259","1160–1215":"1160–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1231":"1231","1220":"1220","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Le Brook, Ilchester, Somerset, England":"Ilchester, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1180–1231":"1180–1231","1220–1259":"1220–1259","1160–1215":"1160–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1231":"1231","1220":"1220","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Le Brook, Ilchester, Somerset, England":"Ilchester, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1180–1231":"1180–1231","1220–1259":"1220–1259","1160–1215":"1160–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Décédée","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1231":"1231","1220":"1220","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Le Brook, Ilchester, Somerset, England":"Ilchester, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Brooke est né en 1180, à Ilchester, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Arundel De Brooke, avait 20 ans et sa mère, Edeline de Cobham, avait 18 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1231, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 51 ans."},"de":{"1180–1231":"1180–1231","1220–1259":"1220–1259","1160–1215":"1160–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Verst